6... a6 7. e3 b5 8. Qc2 Nb4 9. Qd2 c5 10. a3 Qa5 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. dxc5 b4 13. Ne2 Ne4 14. Qd1 bxa3+ 15. Bd2 Qxc5 16. Rxa3=

making sure your centre is solid and adquently defended is the first step in developing a successful attack. Consequently, the neglect of center is the hallmark of an attack that is doomed to fail. The lesson is that you should never go after the enemy king if you have a weak unsupported center.
! highlighting the major drawback of 6. ...Bd5 because the threat is to capture on d5 winning the strategic long term advantage of the bishop pair for white.

this is better than 9. ...e6 since black gets some form of compensation in a long term damage to whites pawn structure. However, in return black gives up the bishop pair and gives white an extra centre pawn.

black has given up the long term advantage of the bishop pair in exchange for a permanate target on f3. However, the drawback is that white now has an extra pawn in the center so black now has to watch out for a timely e4 break.

Black already is feeling the need to take drastic measures. Since any quiet moves like ...e6 would allow white to build a overwhelming center with 10. Bb5 Be7(10. ...a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Rg1 c5 13. dxc5 looks better for white) 11. e4 0-0 12. Be3 and white can take his time building on his space advantage.
